GIT COMMIT !! 

Before Commit we have to stage the files. 
> *Staging -*
--The staging environment (or staging area) is like a waiting room for your changes.
  You use it to tell Git exactly which files you want to include in your next commit.
  Here are some key commands for staging:- 
     a> git add <file> - Stage a file
     b> git add --all or git add -A - Stage all changes
     c> git status - See what is staged
     d> git restore --staged <file> - Unstage a file

> *Commit -*
--A commit is like a save point in your project.
  Here are some key commands for commits:
           git commit -m "message" - Commit staged changes with a message    [Commit staged changes with a message]
           git commit -a -m "message" - Commit all tracked changes (skip staging)   [Commit all tracked changes (skip staging)]
           git log - See commit history       [See commit history] 

Create an empty commit:
git commit --allow-empty -m "Start project"
Use previous commit message (no editor):
git commit --no-edit
Quickly add staged changes to last commit, keep message:
git commit --amend --no-edit


   




